<subSubSection pageId="13" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="13.[173,660,1283,1729]" pageId="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,301,1363,1384]" pageId="13">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[315,540,1362,1383]" italics="true" pageId="13">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2014" box="[315,516,1362,1383]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hermani">Pujoliclerus hermani</taxonomicName>
is
</emphasis>
distinguishable from other members of the genus by the pale yellow coloration of the elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[173,660,1283,1729]" lastBlockId="13.[707,1193,194,587]" pageId="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,379,1443,1464]" pageId="13">Description. Size</emphasis>
: Length 6.0 mm; width 12.0 mm. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[283,340,1469,1490]" pageId="13">Form</emphasis>
: As in 
<figureCitation box="[428,518,1469,1490]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="22.[175,215,1444,1463]" captionTargetBox="[167,1157,203,1421]" captionTargetId="figure-120@22.[167,1157,192,1421]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Figs. 98–103. Pujoliclerus species, habitus. 98) P. ovatus; 99) P. wappesi; 100) P. amplus; 101) P. flavoapicalus;" pageId="13">Fig. 103</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[533,652,1469,1490]" pageId="13">Integument</emphasis>
: Head mostly yellow, with rectangular black marking on vertex; antenna mostly black, scape mostly yellow, last antennomere yellow; pronotal disc broadly black, sides broadly yellow; elytra light yellow; legs mostly yellow, tibiae infuscated; pterothorax and abdomen brown. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[513,568,1629,1650]" pageId="13">Head</emphasis>
: Eyes as wide as frons (14:14); funicular antennomeres slightly expanded (
<figureCitation box="[369,445,1682,1703]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="8.[175,216,1487,1506]" captionTargetBox="[167,1170,207,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-1@8.[151,1172,183,1487]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs. 21–38. Pujoliclerus species, antennae. 21) P. helvinus; 22) P. maracayensis; 23) P. bilineatus; 24) P. calceatus; 25) P. corumba; 26) P. ovatus; 27) P. wappesi; 28) P. amplus; 29) P. flavoapicalus; 30) P. gilvus; 31) P. hermani; 32) P. alajuela; 33) P. orellana; 34) P. megacavus; 35) P. oxinus; 36) P. alboordinus; 37) P. apolegmus; 38) P. catarina." pageId="13">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[467,545,1682,1703]" pageId="13">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum slightly transverse (40:38), lateral tubercle very prominent (
<figureCitation box="[829,910,194,215]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="18.[175,215,1395,1414]" captionTargetBox="[151,1155,183,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-114@18.[151,1172,183,1383]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs. 48–61. Pujoliclerus species, pronota. 48) P. helvinus; 49) P. maracayensis; 50) P. modestus; 51) P. bilineatus; 52) P. calceatus; 53) P. corumba; 54) P. flavolimbatus; 55) P. ovatus; 56) P. wappesi; 57) P. amplus; 58) P. flavoapicalus; 59) P. gilvus; 60) P. hermani; 61) P. orellana." pageId="13">Fig. 60</figureCitation>
); epipleural fold gradually diminishings to elytral apex; asetiferous punctures prominent to elytral apex. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[980,1084,247,268]" pageId="13">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Tegminal lobes and phallic apex as in 
<figureCitation box="[976,1046,274,295]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="20.[175,215,1170,1189]" captionTargetBox="[164,629,189,1147]" captionTargetId="figure-461@20.[151,638,183,1159]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs. 76–91. Pujoliclerus species, aedeagi. 76) P. helvinus; 77) P. bilineatus; 78) P. calceatus; 79) P. corumba; 80) P. flavolimbatus; 81) P. ovatus (tegmen only); 82) P. wappesi; 83) P. gilvus; 84) P. hermani; 85) P. casselorum; 86) P. catarina (phallus only); 87) P. argus; 88) P. aspigalbus; 89) P. flora; 90) P. posticalis; 91) P. pallidus." pageId="13">Fig. 84</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[707,1193,194,587]" pageId="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,905,300,321]" pageId="13">Natural History.</emphasis>
T h e t y p e w a s c o l l e c t e d during April, from streamside litter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
